1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,240
Three officers at the door.

2
00:00:01,840 --> 00:00:03,380
A piece of paper waved like a warrant

3
00:00:04,082 --> 00:00:04,860
but no real warrant.

4
00:00:05,380 --> 00:00:06,120
They go in anyway.

5
00:00:06,660 --> 00:00:08,180
And what they find ends up thrown out

6
00:00:08,180 --> 00:00:08,540
of court.

7
00:00:09,440 --> 00:00:10,531
That moment —

8
00:00:10,620 --> 00:00:12,400
police forcing their way into an American

9
00:00:12,400 --> 00:00:15,480
home, the courts later refusing to use what

10
00:00:15,480 --> 00:00:16,751
they turned up —

11
00:00:16,752 --> 00:00:18,500
is not a legal technicality.

12
00:00:18,980 --> 00:00:20,480
It is the answer to one of the

13
00:00:20,480 --> 00:00:23,660
most important questions in criminal law: if

14
00:00:23,660 --> 00:00:25,480
the police break the rules to get evidence

15
00:00:25,480 --> 00:00:27,880
against you, can they still use that

16
00:00:27,880 --> 00:00:29,100
evidence to convict you?

17
00:00:29,740 --> 00:00:31,660
Before 1961, in most states,

18
00:00:31,840 --> 00:00:32,540
the answer was yes.

19
00:00:33,600 --> 00:00:35,080
The Fourth Amendment says the government

20
00:00:35,080 --> 00:00:37,180
cannot conduct unreasonable searches.

21
00:00:37,800 --> 00:00:39,560
It has said that since 1791.

22
00:00:40,400 --> 00:00:41,940
But for most of American history,

23
00:00:42,380 --> 00:00:44,840
the amendment had a problem: no one had

24
00:00:44,840 --> 00:00:46,900
figured out what happened when the police

25
00:00:46,900 --> 00:00:47,932
ignored it .

26
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:49,200
The evidence was still there.

27
00:00:49,660 --> 00:00:50,740
The conviction still came.

28
00:00:51,260 --> 00:00:52,520
The right existed on paper,

29
00:00:52,520 --> 00:00:53,480
and nowhere else.

30
00:00:54,380 --> 00:00:55,840
What changed that —

31
00:00:55,920 --> 00:00:57,960
what gave the Fourth Amendment actual teeth

32
00:00:57,960 --> 00:00:59,851
in a real courtroom —

33
00:00:59,852 --> 00:01:01,440
was a search gone wrong in Cleveland,

34
00:01:01,560 --> 00:01:04,740
Ohio, in 1957, and a woman named Dollree

35
00:01:04,740 --> 00:01:05,532
Mapp .

36
00:01:06,080 --> 00:01:08,420
Over the next twelve minutes: what happened

37
00:01:08,420 --> 00:01:10,980
at her door, what the Supreme Court did

38
00:01:10,980 --> 00:01:12,960
about it, and why the rule they created

39
00:01:12,960 --> 00:01:15,080
is still the most argued-over protection in

40
00:01:15,080 --> 00:01:16,040
American criminal law.

41
00:01:16,920 --> 00:01:19,061
It is May 23, 1957 .

42
00:01:20,100 --> 00:01:21,860
Dollree Mapp lives on the upper floor of

43
00:01:21,860 --> 00:01:23,100
a house in Cleveland, Ohio.

44
00:01:23,780 --> 00:01:25,840
On that afternoon, Cleveland police officers

45
00:01:25,840 --> 00:01:27,271
arrive at her door .

46
00:01:27,280 --> 00:01:29,240
They are looking for a suspect in a

47
00:01:29,240 --> 00:01:31,126
bombing case —

48
00:01:31,127 --> 00:01:32,100
a man they believe may be hiding in

49
00:01:32,100 --> 00:01:34,513
the house .

50
00:01:34,514 --> 00:01:35,014
They knock.

51
00:01:35,015 --> 00:01:35,840
Mapp does not let them in.

52
00:01:36,300 --> 00:01:37,180
She calls her attorney.

53
00:01:37,800 --> 00:01:38,860
The officers wait outside.

54
00:01:39,700 --> 00:01:41,796
Then they go in anyway .

55
00:01:41,797 --> 00:01:43,160
An officer holds up a piece of paper

56
00:01:44,662 --> 00:01:45,300
waving it as if it were a warrant

57
00:01:45,300 --> 00:01:48,481
authorizing the search .

58
00:01:48,482 --> 00:01:49,640
Mapp grabs for it; the officers take it

59
00:01:49,640 --> 00:01:49,920
back.

60
00:01:50,860 --> 00:01:53,020
Later, no valid warrant will be produced in

61
00:01:53,020 --> 00:01:53,260
court.

62
00:01:53,800 --> 00:01:56,200
Whether one ever existed at all will remain

63
00:01:56,200 --> 00:01:57,395
disputed —

64
00:01:57,396 --> 00:01:59,840
but what is not disputed is this: no

65
00:01:59,840 --> 00:02:01,852
valid warrant was ever shown .

66
00:02:02,300 --> 00:02:03,220
A warrant, to be clear,

67
00:02:03,460 --> 00:02:05,660
is a judge's written authorization for a

68
00:02:05,660 --> 00:02:06,320
specific search.

69
00:02:06,960 --> 00:02:08,920
To get one, police have to show a

70
00:02:08,920 --> 00:02:10,860
judge they have good reason —

71
00:02:10,861 --> 00:02:12,420
what the law calls probable cause.

72
00:02:13,080 --> 00:02:14,820
It is the check on police power the

73
00:02:14,820 --> 00:02:16,780
Fourth Amendment was designed to require.

74
00:02:17,360 --> 00:02:19,060
A piece of paper waved through a window

75
00:02:19,060 --> 00:02:19,780
is not one.

76
00:02:20,560 --> 00:02:22,160
The officers search the house.

77
00:02:22,160 --> 00:02:24,200
They do not find the bombing suspect.

78
00:02:25,060 --> 00:02:26,513
They do find something else —

79
00:02:27,100 --> 00:02:29,065
material they say breaks an Ohio law .

80
00:02:29,420 --> 00:02:31,260
They arrest Dollree Mapp not for anything

81
00:02:31,260 --> 00:02:33,440
related to the bombing, but for what the

82
00:02:33,440 --> 00:02:35,445
warrantless search turned up .

83
00:02:35,740 --> 00:02:38,580
She is tried, convicted, and sentenced under

84
00:02:38,580 --> 00:02:39,720
that Ohio law .

85
00:02:40,080 --> 00:02:41,115
And that conviction —

86
00:02:41,580 --> 00:02:43,559
not any bombing, not the suspect —

87
00:02:43,640 --> 00:02:45,920
is what eventually reaches the Supreme Court

88
00:02:45,920 --> 00:02:46,840
of the United States.

89
00:02:47,620 --> 00:02:49,640
But to get there, first she has to

90
00:02:49,640 --> 00:02:49,900
lose.

91
00:02:49,900 --> 00:02:52,540
And the reason she loses reveals a gap

92
00:02:52,540 --> 00:02:54,600
in American law that most people never knew

93
00:02:54,600 --> 00:02:55,060
existed.

94
00:02:56,160 --> 00:02:56,640
Here is the gap.

95
00:02:57,360 --> 00:02:59,300
The Fourth Amendment, as of 1957,

96
00:02:59,700 --> 00:03:00,900
already applied to the states.

97
00:03:01,560 --> 00:03:03,560
A 1949 Supreme Court case,

98
00:03:04,400 --> 00:03:04,680
Wolf v.

99
00:03:05,060 --> 00:03:07,309
Colorado, had settled that much .

100
00:03:07,800 --> 00:03:09,360
States could not conduct unreasonable

101
00:03:09,360 --> 00:03:10,118
searches —

102
00:03:10,500 --> 00:03:11,723
that was clear .

103
00:03:12,120 --> 00:03:14,480
What Wolf had not done was specify what

104
00:03:14,480 --> 00:03:15,941
happened next .

105
00:03:15,942 --> 00:03:17,760
If a state officer conducted an illegal

106
00:03:17,760 --> 00:03:19,720
search and found something, did that

107
00:03:19,720 --> 00:03:21,140
evidence have to be thrown out?

108
00:03:21,940 --> 00:03:23,560
Wolf said: not necessarily.

109
00:03:24,540 --> 00:03:26,020
States were free to handle the problem

110
00:03:26,020 --> 00:03:27,491
however they chose .

111
00:03:27,660 --> 00:03:29,640
And many states chose to use the evidence

112
00:03:29,640 --> 00:03:29,960
anyway.

113
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:32,560
Federal courts had operated under a

114
00:03:32,560 --> 00:03:35,041
different rule since 1914 —

115
00:03:35,042 --> 00:03:36,520
a case called Weeks v.

116
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:37,993
United States .

117
00:03:38,460 --> 00:03:40,300
Weeks established what lawyers call the

118
00:03:40,300 --> 00:03:43,100
exclusionary rule: evidence obtained through

119
00:03:43,100 --> 00:03:45,300
an illegal search cannot be used in a

120
00:03:45,300 --> 00:03:46,109
federal prosecution .

121
00:03:46,800 --> 00:03:47,920
The logic was simple.

122
00:03:47,920 --> 00:03:50,180
If the government breaks the law to get

123
00:03:50,180 --> 00:03:52,720
evidence, and then uses that evidence to

124
00:03:52,720 --> 00:03:55,140
convict you, the court itself becomes a

125
00:03:55,140 --> 00:03:56,320
participant in the lawbreaking.

126
00:03:57,520 --> 00:03:59,100
But Mapp's case was in a state court,

127
00:03:59,480 --> 00:04:01,595
not a federal one .

128
00:04:01,596 --> 00:04:02,600
And Ohio was one of the states that,

129
00:04:02,880 --> 00:04:04,800
under Wolf, was allowed to use what an

130
00:04:04,800 --> 00:04:07,953
illegal search turned up .

131
00:04:07,954 --> 00:04:08,100
The Fourth Amendment existed.

132
00:04:08,760 --> 00:04:10,580
The search was almost certainly illegal.

133
00:04:11,180 --> 00:04:12,798
And it did not matter .

134
00:04:13,060 --> 00:04:13,920
She is convicted.

135
00:04:14,540 --> 00:04:15,240
Her lawyers appeal.

136
00:04:15,240 --> 00:04:17,560
The Ohio Supreme Court upholds the

137
00:04:17,560 --> 00:04:18,383
conviction .

138
00:04:18,720 --> 00:04:20,040
Then the case goes to Washington.

139
00:04:21,060 --> 00:04:22,680
Her attorneys arrive at the Supreme Court

140
00:04:22,680 --> 00:04:24,740
primarily to argue about whether the state

141
00:04:24,740 --> 00:04:26,960
law she was convicted under was even

142
00:04:26,960 --> 00:04:27,600
constitutional.

143
00:04:28,420 --> 00:04:30,989
The exclusionary rule —

144
00:04:30,990 --> 00:04:32,080
whether the evidence should have been thrown

145
00:04:32,080 --> 00:04:34,432
out —

146
00:04:34,433 --> 00:04:35,280
is raised almost as an afterthought.

147
00:04:36,220 --> 00:04:36,500
Almost.

148
00:04:37,500 --> 00:04:39,240
Because the Supreme Court is about to do

149
00:04:39,240 --> 00:04:40,980
something no one in the courtroom fully

150
00:04:40,980 --> 00:04:41,560
anticipated.

151
00:04:42,220 --> 00:04:44,060
It is about to settle a much larger

152
00:04:44,060 --> 00:04:46,160
question than the one anyone thought they

153
00:04:46,160 --> 00:04:46,660
were arguing.

154
00:04:47,640 --> 00:04:50,380
On June 19, 1961, the Supreme Court issues

155
00:04:50,380 --> 00:04:51,760
its decision in Mapp v.

156
00:04:51,760 --> 00:04:52,597
Ohio .

157
00:04:53,240 --> 00:04:54,000
Justice Tom C.

158
00:04:54,240 --> 00:04:55,480
Clark writes the opinion of the Court,

159
00:04:55,480 --> 00:04:57,171
over three dissents .

160
00:04:57,580 --> 00:04:59,540
The Court does not simply resolve whether

161
00:04:59,540 --> 00:05:01,100
the Ohio law is constitutional.

162
00:05:01,760 --> 00:05:03,160
It reaches back to Wolf v.

163
00:05:03,160 --> 00:05:04,761
Colorado —

164
00:05:04,762 --> 00:05:07,060
the 1949 case that had let states use

165
00:05:07,060 --> 00:05:09,055
illegally seized evidence —

166
00:05:09,056 --> 00:05:10,844
and it overrules it .

167
00:05:10,845 --> 00:05:12,800
After twelve years, the loophole is closed.

168
00:05:13,560 --> 00:05:15,700
The reasoning turns on a single principle.

169
00:05:16,420 --> 00:05:18,460
If the Fourth Amendment is a real right,

170
00:05:18,920 --> 00:05:20,860
there has to be a real remedy when

171
00:05:20,860 --> 00:05:23,103
it is violated .

172
00:05:23,104 --> 00:05:24,480
The exclusionary rule —

173
00:05:24,481 --> 00:05:26,202
throwing out the evidence —

174
00:05:26,203 --> 00:05:26,340
is that remedy.

175
00:05:26,960 --> 00:05:28,420
Without it, the Court says,

176
00:05:28,940 --> 00:05:31,160
the constitutional protection becomes "a

177
00:05:31,160 --> 00:05:32,056
form of words" .

178
00:05:32,400 --> 00:05:34,780
A guarantee that no one can actually use

179
00:05:34,780 --> 00:05:35,560
is not a guarantee.

180
00:05:36,480 --> 00:05:38,180
The point is not to help guilty defendants.

181
00:05:38,820 --> 00:05:40,740
The point is to deter the police from

182
00:05:40,740 --> 00:05:44,080
breaking the law in the first place —

183
00:05:44,081 --> 00:05:44,380
and to keep the courts from becoming

184
00:05:44,380 --> 00:05:47,793
instruments of constitutional violations .

185
00:05:47,794 --> 00:05:48,840
If you want to use evidence,

186
00:05:49,440 --> 00:05:49,940
get a warrant.

187
00:05:50,660 --> 00:05:51,360
Follow the rules.

188
00:05:51,980 --> 00:05:53,700
Do not force your way in with a

189
00:05:53,700 --> 00:05:54,300
piece of paper.

190
00:05:55,240 --> 00:05:57,460
The holding is straightforward: illegally

191
00:05:57,460 --> 00:05:59,149
seized evidence is thrown out —

192
00:05:59,440 --> 00:06:01,400
the exclusionary rule now applies to the

193
00:06:01,400 --> 00:06:02,267
states .

194
00:06:02,440 --> 00:06:04,280
Every state court in the country is now

195
00:06:04,280 --> 00:06:06,320
bound by the same rule that federal courts

196
00:06:06,320 --> 00:06:09,887
had operated under since 1914 .

197
00:06:09,888 --> 00:06:12,312
Where most criminal cases actually happen —

198
00:06:12,313 --> 00:06:13,698
in state courtrooms —

199
00:06:13,699 --> 00:06:15,280
the Fourth Amendment finally has a

200
00:06:15,280 --> 00:06:16,469
consequence .

201
00:06:17,020 --> 00:06:18,728
Dollree Mapp's conviction is reversed .

202
00:06:19,120 --> 00:06:20,860
The search that started it all is ruled

203
00:06:20,860 --> 00:06:22,860
to have violated her constitutional rights,

204
00:06:23,400 --> 00:06:25,240
and the evidence from that search cannot be

205
00:06:25,240 --> 00:06:26,463
used against her .

206
00:06:26,620 --> 00:06:28,060
It is a resounding win.

207
00:06:28,500 --> 00:06:30,260
And it carries a cost that no one

208
00:06:30,260 --> 00:06:30,760
can ignore.

209
00:06:31,640 --> 00:06:33,820
The exclusionary rule does something that

210
00:06:33,820 --> 00:06:35,340
has troubled people ever since it was

211
00:06:35,340 --> 00:06:35,800
created.

212
00:06:36,420 --> 00:06:38,160
It can require a court to throw out

213
00:06:38,160 --> 00:06:39,799
reliable evidence —

214
00:06:39,800 --> 00:06:42,080
evidence that is true, that demonstrates

215
00:06:42,080 --> 00:06:42,675
what happened —

216
00:06:42,740 --> 00:06:45,231
because of the way it was obtained .

217
00:06:45,660 --> 00:06:48,260
In 1926, a New York judge named Benjamin

218
00:06:48,260 --> 00:06:50,940
Cardozo put the objection as bluntly as it

219
00:06:50,940 --> 00:06:51,540
can be put.

220
00:06:52,120 --> 00:06:53,620
If the police bungle a search,

221
00:06:53,740 --> 00:06:56,100
he wrote, "the criminal is to go free

222
00:06:56,100 --> 00:06:58,850
because the constable has blundered" .

223
00:06:58,851 --> 00:07:00,980
The guilty person walks not because the

224
00:07:00,980 --> 00:07:03,480
evidence was wrong, but because the process

225
00:07:03,480 --> 00:07:05,270
that produced it was .

226
00:07:05,580 --> 00:07:07,780
That tension is real and it has never

227
00:07:07,780 --> 00:07:08,320
gone away.

228
00:07:09,300 --> 00:07:10,860
Defenders of the rule argue that the

229
00:07:10,860 --> 00:07:13,047
deterrence is worth the cost —

230
00:07:13,048 --> 00:07:15,320
that without the consequence, there is no

231
00:07:15,320 --> 00:07:17,120
reason for police to respect the warrant

232
00:07:17,120 --> 00:07:18,773
requirement at all .

233
00:07:19,300 --> 00:07:20,780
Critics argue that the cure sometimes

234
00:07:20,780 --> 00:07:23,020
punishes society more than it punishes the

235
00:07:23,020 --> 00:07:24,817
officer who made the mistake .

236
00:07:25,120 --> 00:07:27,180
The Supreme Court itself has spent decades

237
00:07:27,180 --> 00:07:28,400
navigating that tension.

238
00:07:28,940 --> 00:07:30,180
It has not stayed still.

239
00:07:31,180 --> 00:07:32,640
Later rulings carved out limits and

240
00:07:32,640 --> 00:07:34,722
exceptions to what Mapp established —

241
00:07:35,220 --> 00:07:36,920
among them a good-faith exception,

242
00:07:36,920 --> 00:07:39,860
for cases where officers acted on a warrant

243
00:07:39,860 --> 00:07:41,660
they reasonably believed was valid,

244
00:07:42,060 --> 00:07:43,560
even if it turned out to be defective

245
00:07:44,300 --> 00:07:46,400
The rule today is narrower than it was

246
00:07:46,400 --> 00:07:48,053
in 1961 .

247
00:07:48,340 --> 00:07:49,380
But the core holds.

248
00:07:49,900 --> 00:07:51,760
An illegal search can still sink a case

249
00:07:51,760 --> 00:07:53,692
in state court .

250
00:07:53,693 --> 00:07:54,940
The warrant requirement still has

251
00:07:54,940 --> 00:07:55,560
consequences.

252
00:07:56,440 --> 00:07:57,897
Mapp is the reason for that .

253
00:07:58,180 --> 00:08:00,388
What the case really established —

254
00:08:00,800 --> 00:08:02,760
what makes it more than an obscure

255
00:08:02,760 --> 00:08:03,803
procedural ruling —

256
00:08:04,450 --> 00:08:06,500
is that rights without remedies are

257
00:08:06,500 --> 00:08:06,940
fictions.

258
00:08:07,620 --> 00:08:10,280
The Fourth Amendment had existed for a

259
00:08:10,280 --> 00:08:12,440
hundred and seventy years before Mapp.

260
00:08:12,440 --> 00:08:14,140
It took a forced entry,

261
00:08:14,840 --> 00:08:17,380
a piece of paper waved as a warrant,

262
00:08:17,380 --> 00:08:17,807
and one woman's conviction to make it real

263
00:08:17,849 --> 00:08:19,515
in a state courtroom .

264
00:08:19,820 --> 00:08:21,020
Step back from the facts,

265
00:08:21,020 --> 00:08:23,220
and the shape of this case is almost

266
00:08:23,220 --> 00:08:24,160
counterintuitive.

267
00:08:24,740 --> 00:08:26,360
The landmark that reshaped

268
00:08:26,360 --> 00:08:28,660
search-and-seizure law in every state did

269
00:08:28,660 --> 00:08:30,660
not begin with a dramatic confrontation.

270
00:08:31,360 --> 00:08:33,520
It began with a bombing suspect who was

271
00:08:33,520 --> 00:08:35,740
never found, a search that produced

272
00:08:35,740 --> 00:08:38,400
something else entirely, and a conviction

273
00:08:38,400 --> 00:08:40,180
that no one at the time thought would

274
00:08:40,180 --> 00:08:41,557
matter very much .

275
00:08:41,960 --> 00:08:42,620
And yet it did.

276
00:08:43,440 --> 00:08:44,649
Mapp, Gideon, Miranda —

277
00:08:45,880 --> 00:08:48,080
these three cases are not coincidences

278
00:08:48,080 --> 00:08:49,280
stacked next to each other.

279
00:08:49,780 --> 00:08:51,540
They are three pieces of the same shift:

280
00:08:52,060 --> 00:08:53,940
applying your constitutional rights to the

281
00:08:53,940 --> 00:08:56,320
states, making them real where you actually

282
00:08:56,320 --> 00:08:56,497
encounter the law .

283
00:08:58,080 --> 00:08:59,820
Miranda told police what they have to say

284
00:08:59,820 --> 00:09:00,680
when they arrest you.

285
00:09:01,300 --> 00:09:03,380
Gideon guaranteed you a lawyer if you cannot

286
00:09:03,380 --> 00:09:04,000
afford one.

287
00:09:04,660 --> 00:09:06,560
Mapp answered what happens when the police

288
00:09:06,560 --> 00:09:08,673
break the rules before any of that .

289
00:09:08,680 --> 00:09:10,440
The Fourth Amendment says the government

290
00:09:10,440 --> 00:09:11,840
cannot search your home without

291
00:09:11,840 --> 00:09:12,540
justification.

292
00:09:13,540 --> 00:09:15,180
Mapp is the answer to the follow-up question

293
00:09:15,180 --> 00:09:18,080
nobody asked loudly enough for decades: or

294
00:09:18,080 --> 00:09:18,360
what?

295
00:09:19,180 --> 00:09:20,720
Or the evidence gets thrown out.

296
00:09:21,120 --> 00:09:21,800
That is the rule.

297
00:09:22,420 --> 00:09:23,500
That is what the case cost,

298
00:09:23,500 --> 00:09:24,440
and what it bought.

299
00:09:25,280 --> 00:09:27,536
Next episode: we pull back further —

300
00:09:27,537 --> 00:09:30,000
to who decides what counts as a crime

301
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:32,200
in the first place, and whether the law

302
00:09:32,200 --> 00:09:33,800
applies to the people who write it.

303
00:09:34,600 --> 00:09:36,700
Until then: now you know what it took

304
00:09:36,700 --> 00:09:38,320
to make the Fourth Amendment more than

305
00:09:38,320 --> 00:09:38,620
words.
